                                                                                                               Govt clears REC follow-on public offer
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	New Delhi, Oct. 29: The government today approved Rural Electrification Corporation Limiteds proposal for a follow-on public offer to sell a 20 per cent stake.        
	(The) Cabinet Committee on Economic Affairs today approved 5 per cent offloading of governments stake as well as an infusion of 15 per cent fresh equity in REC, home minister P. Chidambaram told reporters after the meeting.        
	He said the stake would be sold in the current financial year and the price determined by the government after considering market conditions.        
	Industry sources said based on todays market price of Rs 197.30,the issue size of REC might be around Rs 3,400 crore. Of this, REC may get Rs 2,500 crore, and the government, Rs 900 crore.         
	Chidambaram said the proceeds would be used by REC for investment. Part of the shares will be for the employees.        
	REC provides loan assistance to state power utilities for investments in rural electrification schemes. Its loan book stands at about Rs 61,000 crore.         
	RECs second-quarter net profit rose 60.14 per cent to Rs 494.36 crore over the same period last year. Total income rose to Rs 1,622.95 crore from Rs 1,173.58 crore.         
	Paddy purchase        
	The government today announced a bonus of Rs 50 per quintal to farmers on paddy to boost procurement for the public distribution system, amid fears of a slump in production.        
	The bonus will be provided over and above the minimum support price of Rs 950 per quintal for the common variety and Rs 980 per quintal for the superior variety during this kharif marketing season (October-September).        
	The government has allowed ONGC Videsh to invest about $174 million more in two gas blocks off Myanmar.        
	Meanwhile, the Union cabinet today decided that sugar mills would have to pay Rs 50 more to cane growers in the 2009-2010 season, The benchmark price will be Rs 129.84 a quintal.                                                                                                                                        
